  "user": "Translate these text blocks from complex_integration.html:\n\n[block_0] <p>: [[i class=\"fa-solid fa-list\"]][[/i]]Contents\n\n[block_1] <li>: [[a href=\"#section1\"]]Contour integral[[/a]]\n\n[block_2] <li>: [[a href=\"#section2\"]]Numerical evaluation 1[[/a]]\n\n[block_3] <li>: [[a href=\"#section3\"]]Numerical evaluation 2[[/a]]\n\n[block_4] <li>: [[a href=\"#section4\"]]Properties[[/a]]\n\n[block_5] <li>: [[a href=\"#section5\"]]Antiderivatives[[/a]]\n\n[block_6] <h1>: Complex Integration\n\n[block_7] <p>: \n                        The magic and power of calculus ultimately rests on the amazing fact that differentiation and\n                        integration\n                        are mutually inverse operations. And, just as complex functions enjoy remarkable\n                        differentiability\n                        properties not shared by their real counterparts, so the sublime beauty of complex integration\n                        goes\n                        far\n                        beyond its real progenitor.\n                    \n\n[block_8] <h2>: Contour integral\n\n[block_9] <p>: \n                    Consider a contour @@math:39:ca7568@@ parametrized by @@math:40:cb5f39@@ for @@math:41:982581@@ We define the\n                    [[em]]integral[[/em]]\n                    of the complex function along @@math:42:2ec014@@ to be the complex number\n                    @@math:7:03f085@@\n                    Here we assume that @@math:43:cec136@@ is piecewise continuous on the interval\n                    @@math:44:90e9d4@@ and refer to the function @@math:45:3a3f89@@ as being piecewise continuous on @@math:46:93ffce@@\n                    Since @@math:47:4130d8@@ is a contour, @@math:48:9e2573@@ is also piecewise continuous on @@math:49:fc895a@@;\n                    and so the existence of integral (\\ref{contour-integral}) is ensured.\n                \n\n[block_10] <p>: \n                    The right hand side of (\\ref{c